revision.text:
{{Orphan|date=August 2015}}
The '''American Standard Safety System''', or ASSS, is a connection system for [[gas cylinder]]s with a volume exceeding 25 cubic feet. The connections differ in thread type and size, right and left handed threading, internal and external threading, and nipple-seat design. This variability reduces the risk of errors such as administering the wrong gas to a patient, or utilizing equipment calibrated for one gas with another. However, as there are only 26 connections for the 62 gases and mixtures recognized by the [[Compressed Gas Association|CGA]], connections are not unique.<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Wilkins | first1 = Robert L. | last2 = Stoller | first2 = James K. | last3 = Kacmarek | first3 = Robert M. | title = Egan's Fundamentals of Respiratory Care | edition = 9, illustrated | publisher = Mosby/Elsevier | year = 2009 | isbn = 978-0-323-03657-3}}<!--| accessdate = 2011-11-04 --></ref>
Connection specifications will be listed in cylinder catalogs as a list of abbreviations and numbers, such as that for O<sub>2</sub>, CGA-540 0.903-14NGO-RH-Ext. This means that the [[Compressed Gas Association]] has classified this connection as number 540, the thread bore is 0.903&nbsp;inches, with 14 threads per inch. The connection is right-handed (RH) and must be turned clock-wise to tighten. The threading is external, so the connections of the cylinder and the attached equipment must be fixed together using a nipple, which is signified by NGO. A nipple is a bolt which fits together two male connections. Internal (Int) threading allows for equipment to be screwed directly onto the cylinder outlet.<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Cairo | first1 = Jimmy M. | last2 = Pilbeam | first2 = Susan P. | title = Mosby's Respiratory Care Equipment | edition = 8, illustrated | publisher = Mosby/Elsevier | year = 2010 | isbn = 978-0-323-05176-7}}<!--| accessdate = 2011-11-04 --></ref>
==See also== * [[Compressed Gas Association]] * [[Pin Index Safety System]] * [[Diameter Index Safety System]]
==References== {{reflist}}
{{DEFAULTSORT:American Standard Safety System}} [[Category:Pressure vessels]] [[Category:Anesthetic equipment]] [[Category:Gas technologies]]

A '''blown oil''' is a [[drying oil]] which has been modified through an oxidative process.

==Description==
[[Oil]]s are "blown" through partial [[oxidation]] of the oil at elevated temperatures. A typical blowing process involves heating the oil to {{convert|70|to|120|C}} and passing air through the liquid.<ref name="doi1">{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1108/eb042356| title = Blown (air oxidised) vegetable & marine oils & paint manufacture| journal = Pigment & Resin Technology| volume = 16| issue = 5| pages = 7| year = 1987| last1 = Lower | first1 = E. S. }}</ref> The modification causes the formation of C-O-C and C-C cross links, and [[hydroxyl]] and [[carboxyl]] functional groups.<ref name="doi1"/>

Blown oils are chemically different from oils modified only by heating,<ref name="doi1"/> which are known as [[stand oil]]s.<ref>{{citation| url = http://www.seatons-uk.co.uk/home.aspx?s=62&r=109&p=453| title = The differences between stand oils and blown oils| work = www.seatons-uk.co.uk| accessdate = 1 February 2015}}</ref>

Some common types of oils that can be blown include [[linseed oil]], [[rapeseed oil]], [[castor oil]] and [[soybean oil]].

